<h4 id="step-2-configure-a-build-process">Step 2. Configure a build process</h4>
<p>Design System stylesheets use <a href="https://sass-lang.com/">Sass</a>, a preprocessor for CSS. Sass allows us to systematize our styles, through the use of <a href="https://sass-lang.com/blog/the-module-system-is-launched">module</a> organization, <a href="https://sass-lang.com/guide" title="Sass: Sass Basics">variables, functions, and more</a>.</p>
<p>To bundle Design System styles with your own styles (as well as reuse, import, and configure specific parts of it), we will ensure you have set up Sass and properly configured a <strong>build process</strong> to combine them.</p>
<details>
  <summary>Info: What is a build process?</summary>
  <div>
    A build process takes source code files, runs certain tasks on them (like optimizations), and produces production files. Source code files can use third-party tools that make development easier but that browsers don't understand. Production files are intended to only be seen and processed by a browser, and are optimized for performance.
  </div>
</details>

<details>
  <summary>Step 2.1. Installing gulp.js</summary>
  <div>

<p><a href="https://gulpjs.com/">gulp.js</a> is the recommended build tool. To set it up, from your project&#39;s root directory, install <code>gulp</code> and <code>gulp-dart-sass</code>.</p>
<pre><code class="language-terminal">npm install --save-dev gulp gulp-dart-sass
</code></pre>
  </div>
</details>

<details>
  <summary>Step 2.2. Adding a gulpfile.js</summary>
  <div>

<p>Then, copy the below code to a <b>gulpfile.js</b> file that you place in the root folder of your project.</p>
<ol>
<li>Replace <code>PATH_TO_UNCOMPILED_ASSETS</code> with the path to your project&#39;s uncompiled code (for example, <code>./assets</code>).</li>
<li>Replace <code>PATH_TO_COMPILED_ASSETS</code> with the path to your project&#39;s static production files (for example, <code>./public</code>).</li>
</ol>
<details>
  <summary>gulpfile.js</summary>
  <div>

<pre><code class="language-js">// Import gulp and utilities.
import gulp from &quot;gulp&quot;;
const { task, watch, src, dest, series } = gulp;

// Import Sass.
import sass from &quot;gulp-dart-sass&quot;;

// Configure project paths.
const inputPath = &quot;PATH_TO_UNCOMPILED_ASSETS&quot;;
const outputPath = &quot;PATH_TO_COMPILED_ASSETS&quot;;

// This function specifies what to do with a project&#39;s styles.
const stylesTask = () =&gt; {
  // Take files from the input path.
  return src(`${inputPath}/styles/**/*.scss`)
    // Process them with Sass.
    .pipe(sass({
      // Do not change.
      includePaths: [&quot;./node_modules/@txch/tcds/src/styles&quot;],
    }))
    // Output files to the output path.
    .pipe(dest(`${outputPath}/styles/`));
};

// Register the styles task.
task(&quot;styles&quot;, stylesTask);
// Register a task to watch the input path for changes, and re-run the task
// when one is detected.
task(&quot;watch&quot;, function watcher() {
  watch(`${inputPath}/styles/`, stylesTask);
});

// Define the default task to run when the `gulp` command is executed.
task(&quot;default&quot;, series([&quot;styles&quot;, &quot;watch&quot;]));
</code></pre>
  </div>
</details>
</div>
</details>

<details>
  <summary>Step 2.3. Running the build process</summary>
  <div>

<p>Now, any time you want to compile your CSS, run <code>gulp</code> from the command line. It will continuously watch for saved changes to any <code>.scss</code> file, and re-run the styles task from the gulpfile.
  </div></p>
</details>

