<h4 id="step-3-configure-a-module-bundler">Step 3. Configure a module bundler</h4>
<p>Design System JavaScript is organized as <a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Guide/Modules">modules</a>. To bundle these modules along with your other JavaScript code, we recommend a module bundler like <a href="https://webpack.js.org/">webpack.js</a>.</p>
<details>
  <summary>Info: What is a module bundler?</summary>
  <div>
    In its simplest use case, a module bundler combines separate code files into one file, making sure that any dependencies between the different files are sufficiently connected, and that the final bundle file is optimized for performance. We only use a module bundler for JavaScript, because CSS module bundling is handled by Sass's own module system.
  </div>
</details>

<details>
  <summary>Step 3.1. Installing webpack.js</summary>
  <div>

<p>To set it up, from your project&#39;s root directory, install <code>webpack</code> and <code>webpack-cli</code>.</p>
<pre><code class="language-terminal">npm install --save-dev webpack webpack-cli
</code></pre>
  </div>
</details>

<details>
  <summary>Step 3.2. Adding a webpack.config.js file</summary>
  <div>

<p>Then, copy the below code to a <b>webpack.config.js</b> file that you place in the root folder of your project.</p>
<ol>
<li>Replace <code>MAIN_SCRIPT_FILE</code> with the &quot;entry&quot; script (a file from which you import all your other scripts, for example, <code>./assets/scripts/index.js</code>).</li>
<li>Replace <code>PATH_TO_COMPILED_SCRIPTS</code> with the folder you want bundled scripts to go (for example, <code>./public/scripts</code>).</li>
</ol>
<details>
  <summary>webpack.config.js</summary>
  <div>

<pre><code class="language-js">import { join, resolve } from &quot;path&quot;;

export default {
  entry: &quot;MAIN_SCRIPT_FILE&quot;,
  output: {
    path: join(resolve(), &quot;PATH_TO_COMPILED_SCRIPTS&quot;),
    filename: &quot;main.js&quot;,
  },
};
</code></pre>
<p>  <b>Tip:</b> You can name the final bundle whatever you want. In the above example, we chose <code>main.js</code>.
  </div></p>
</details>
</div>
</details>

<details>
  <summary>Step 3.3. Running a bundle process</summary>
  <div>

<p>To actually bundle JavaScript modules, go to the <code>package.json</code> file, and inside the <code>scripts</code> object, add the below line:</p>
<pre><code class="language-javascript">&quot;build&quot;: &quot;webpack&quot;
</code></pre>
<p>Now, you can run <code>npm run build</code> to bundle all JavaScript assets together.
  </div></p>
</details>

